    value: 《주역》태(泰)괘에 있는 말로, 성이 무너져 해자로 돌아간다는 뜻이다. 황(隍)은 해자를 말함.
  - key: '[주-D002] 전제(筌蹄) : '
    value: 전(筌)은 물고기를 잡는 통발이며, 제(蹄)는 토끼를 잡는 그물이다. 그런데 통발이나 그물은 잡고 난 후에는 잊어버리는 것으로, 여기서는 목적을 이룬 다음에는 소용없는 것을 말한다.
english:
  title: Preface to the Mirror of Warning for the Tang Emperor
  author: Choe Hang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the eighth year of His Majesty's reign, in the summer of the fifth month, I was summoned and told: "Our King Sejong, having studied the records of antiquity and sought to establish precedents for posterity, once culled the deeds of Tang's Ming Emperor and composed one hundred sixty-eight songs with his own hand, setting forth the facts section by section. In these paired verses, success and failure become manifest; through the lament and song, warnings shine clear. The language is graceful yet luminous, flowing yet profound—truly a mirror for ten thousand ages. I have long pondered the noble policies of my predecessors and striven to restore their lasting traces, yet I fear the narrative remains too sparse for limited learning to encompass. You must further refine and augment it, and also append commentary." Unworthy though I am, I dared not decline, and humbly accepting the command, I collaborated with others to examine various texts, making modest additions and corrections, affixing explanations of sounds and meanings, and appending those deeds not contained within the songs, so that understanding might be enriched. We further gathered scholars to translate into the vernacular, had officials verify the text, ministers review it again, and I undertook a third revision before completing this work for submission. His Majesty named it "The Mirror of Warning for the Tang Emperor" and commanded me to write this preface.

    I humbly submit: The ruler stands as lord of all things, and the heart is master of the body. In a single thought, if reverence prevails, the body finds peace and receives the support of heaven and earth; in a single breath, should negligence creep in, the body faces peril and loses the achievement of ages. Pride and excess spring easily from high station and great wealth, and it is indeed true that order and chaos, rise and fall, hinge upon the subtlest workings of the heart's discipline or laxity. Yet when myriad desires assault the single heart, none proves harder to withstand than the passion of color. Bewitching forms easily cloud the eye; adorned beauty easily binds the breast. Intoxicated, one cannot wake; ensnared, one forgets return. Thus all affairs crumble, all laws grow slack. No son can remonstrate, no minister can correct. Can one hope to avoid disaster and avert ruin? The consort Mei Xi enchanted, and the Xia dynasty fell; Bao Si was favored, and the Zhou perished. The rooster crows at dawn, and the realm is in turmoil—such sayings have come down to us. Jackdaws pecked at Han's well. The calamities wrought upon the realm by fair faces are manifold indeed.

    Considering this: those lost from the start merit little comment. Yet how strange that one man's heart should shift from clarity to darkness, one man's body should see fortune and ruin so utterly reversed. How few have been like Ming Emperor of Tang! At first he abolished internal strife, grasped the mandate of heaven with keen resolve, selected the worthy and employed the talented, swept away all corruption, and saw all lands prosper. The peace of his early reign rivaled that of the Zhenguan era. Yet in his final years, luxury's seed sprouted suddenly, arrogance's winds rose by degrees. He cherished journeys to the eastern palace, forgot the shame of new heights. He indulged the excesses of the Five Yang sisters, rejected the loyal counsel of Zhang Jiuling. He entrusted the wicked to his inner circle and spent the people's blood on sport and revelry. Thus did golden beauty make tumult in the rear palace, and rebel generals lean upon their perches. Heaven's warnings came from above, yet he heeded them not. The people grew distant below, yet he reformed not. When the iron palanquin barely turned south, the imperial carriage had already departed west. He grieved too late at his fathers' remonstrance; he bowed before the threats of eunuchs. Fifty years of glory crumbled in a single dawn—is this not cause for mockery? The vows of paired wings and intertwined branches that once seemed binding—how do they compare to the day the palace women were cast out? His love of cockfights and dancing horses—how does it weigh against the dismissal of censors? When he sought jade in Lanfield, where went his heart to burn it? When he enfeoffed the green-robed concubines, where had his zeal to purge needless offices gone? Yesterday's indulgence, today's disgrace—to this extremity he came. Why was it so? And though he witnessed the ruin wrought by women's charms, how could he not avoid treading that same path himself? Is it not that the heart, being difficult to master, is easily swayed by beauty's power, which corrodes the will and brings ruin to the realm?

    The ancient sages feared the desolation beauty could bring and kept their distance with vigilance. The teaching to preserve position through constant virtue, the warning that few complete what they begin—were these not spoken for this very reason?

    Our realm, since its founding, has seen successive sage-kings maintain unbroken virtue in their conduct and unified principle in their works. The propriety of our house-laws serves as model for a hundred ages; the excellence of our governance transcends a thousand years. King Sejong, ever cautious and diligent, constantly refined the sincerity of self-discipline and deepened the transformative influence of family law. Heaven's gifts endowed him abundantly; his voice became law itself. From his profound reflection came new compositions: he wove the subtle meanings of the Spring and Autumn into flowing melodies, and strict principles shine through effortless grace. A single utterance carries resonance; meanings repeated thrice remain boundless. His songs accord with the eight tones by which sage Shun discerned order and chaos, with the nine songs by which sage Yu warned against destruction—across different ages, the same noble tune. Alas, how sublime!

    Now our present Sovereign, receiving the mandate of heaven, succeeds to that radiant heritage, reverently follows the ways left by his ancestors, and labors to spread their renown. In commanding this compilation, he ensures its brilliance shines forth—surely this is no mere chance. When we take men as our mirror, we see gain and loss; when we take history as our mirror, we know rise and fall. The deeds of Tang's Ming Emperor are among the highest mirrors of all. From this time forward, succeeding generations, contemplating the intent of this song, shall find in its hearing constant cause for grave reflection. Thus shall they awaken with trembling hearts and clear minds. Remembering the flourishing Kaiyuan era, they shall kindle minds open to virtue. Recalling the chaotic Tianbao years, they shall chasten lustful inclinations. They shall regard seduction as a sharp blade, ease as poison. Always let propriety rule the heart; always let will command the passions. In prosperity, harbor fears of ruin; in peace, bear concern for complacency. In revering heaven and attending the people's needs, they shall not slacken for a breath or flag in any endeavor. Thus shall enduring good governance come without strain, and ever-increasing blessings be enjoyed without solicitation.

    Thus this song is surely the essence of how a ruler clarifies the heart and manifests governance—the great teaching of preserving what is achieved and maintaining abundance. The three hundred poems of the *Odes*, with their principle of harmless simplicity, transgress this not; the songs of fair wives who sway, the refined verses of wise women who topple cities—all become but means to this great end. How much more so when our Sovereign pours forth the sacred legacy entrusted to descendants and continues the supreme feeling of honoring his forebears—these transcend the reach of this servant's brush and tongue. Yet surely from this song, the boundless blessings of Chosŏn through ten thousand ages shall only grow deeper and more enduring.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Mei Xi and Bao Si were legendary consorts whose favor led to the downfall of the Xia and Zhou dynasties respectively, establishing a long tradition of cautionary tales about female influence at court.
  - key: ''
    value: The Five Yang sisters refers to the clan of Yang Guifei, the beloved concubine of Ming Emperor whose influence contributed to the An Lushan Rebellion.
  - key: ''
    value: Zhang Jiuling was a loyal minister whose counsel the emperor rejected, exemplifying the theme of a ruler's descent into folly by dismissing wise advisors.
  - key: ''
    value: The Kaiyuan era (713-741) represents the height of Ming Emperor's early reign, while the Tianbao era (742-756) marks its decline and culmination in the devastating An Lushan Rebellion.
